# Deobfuscated Code Analysis

## Deobfuscated Version

```javascript
// Constants
var TAU = 6.283;          // 2π (full circle in radians)
var PHI = 1.618;          // Golden ratio
var SQRT_HALF = 0.707;    // √(1/2)

// Physics/simulation configuration
var config = {
    repulsion: 4000,
    compliance: 0.004,
    refractory: 0.92,      // damping/friction factor
    diffusion: 0.0003,     // centering force
    saturation: 40,         // max number of particles
    resistance: 0.04,
    diastolic: 0.06         // camera smoothing factor
};

// --- NODES (graph vertices) ---
var nodes = [
    { id: 'hub',     label: 'Hub',     r: 26, x: 400, y: 300, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'alpha',   label: 'Alpha',   r: 16, x: 500, y: 200, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'beta',    label: 'Beta',    r: 16, x: 300, y: 400, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'gamma',   label: 'Gamma',   r: 14, x: 250, y: 180, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'delta',   label: 'Delta',   r: 14, x: 550, y: 380, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'epsilon', label: 'Epsilon', r: 12, x: 350, y: 150, vx: 0, vy: 0 }
];

// --- EDGES (graph connections with spring physics) ---
var edges = [
    { a: 'hub', b: 'alpha',   rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
    { a: 'hub', b: 'beta',    rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
    { a: 'hub', b: 'gamma',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
    { a: 'hub', b: 'delta',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
    { a: 'hub', b: 'epsilon', rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
    { a: 'alpha', b: 'beta',    rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
    { a: 'gamma', b: 'delta',   rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
    { a: 'alpha', b: 'epsilon', rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];

// Camera state
var camera = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
var cameraTarget = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

// Particles array
var particles = [];
var frameCount = 0;

// Find a node by ID
function findNode(id) {
    for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
        if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
    }
    return null;
}

// Physics simulation step
function simulate() {
    // 1. Node-to-node REPULSION (Coulomb-like)
    for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
        for (var j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
            var dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
            var dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
            var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
            var force = config.repulsion / (dist * dist);
            var fx = (dx / dist) * force;
            var fy = (dy / dist) * force;
            nodes[i].vx += fx;
            nodes[i].vy += fy;
            nodes[j].vx -= fx;
            nodes[j].vy -= fy;
        }
    }

    // 2. Edge SPRING forces (Hooke's law)
    for (var e = 0; e < edges.length; e++) {
        var nodeA = findNode(edges[e].a);
        var nodeB = findNode(edges[e].b);
        if (!nodeA || !nodeB) continue;

        var dx = nodeB.x - nodeA.x;
        var dy = nodeB.y - nodeA.y;
        var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
        var displacement = dist - edges[e].rest;
        var force = (edges[e].k || config.compliance) * displacement;

        nodeA.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
        nodeA.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
        nodeB.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
        nodeB.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
    }

    // 3. Centering force (diffusion) + damping + integration
    for (var n = 0; n < nodes.length; n++) {
        nodes[n].vx += (400 - nodes[n].x) * config.diffusion;
        nodes[n].vy += (300 - nodes[n].y) * config.diffusion;
        nodes[n].vx *= config.refractory;  // damping
        nodes[n].vy *= config.refractory;
        nodes[n].x += nodes[n].vx;
        nodes[n].y += nodes[n].vy;
    }
}

// Spawn a new particle from a random node
function spawnParticle() {
    if (particles.length >= config.saturation) return;

    var sourceNode = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
    var angle = Math.random() * TAU;
    var speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT_HALF;

    particles.push({
        x: sourceNode.x,
        y: sourceNode.y,
        vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
        vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
        age: 0,
        maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
        size: 0.8 + Math.random() * PHI * SQRT_HALF
    });
}

// Update all particles
function updateParticles() {
    for (var i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        var p = particles[i];
        p.vx *= 1 - config.resistance * 0.125;
        p.vy *= 1 - config.resistance * 0.125;
        p.x += p.vx;
        p.y += p.vy;
        p.age++;
        if (p.age > p.maxAge) {
            particles.splice(i, 1);
        }
    }
}

// Smooth camera interpolation
function updateCamera() {
    camera.x += (cameraTarget.x - camera.x) * config.diastolic;
    camera.y += (cameraTarget.y - camera.y) * config.diastolic;
    camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom) * config.diastolic;
}

// Main loop
function tick() {
    simulate();
    updateParticles();
    if (frameCount % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();
    updateCamera();
    frameCount++;
}

setInterval(tick, 16); // ~60 FPS
```

## What It Does

This is a **force-directed graph simulation** — the kind used to visualize network/node diagrams. Here's the breakdown:

### 🔵 Graph Structure
- **6 nodes**: A central "Hub" connected to Alpha, Beta, Gamma, Delta, and Epsilon
- **8 edges**: Spring connections between nodes (hub-and-spoke with some cross-links)

### ⚡ Physics Engine
The simulation runs three forces each tick:
1. **Repulsion**: All nodes push each other away (inverse-square law, like electric charges)
2. **Spring attraction**: Connected nodes are pulled toward their resting distances (Hooke's law)
3. **Centering gravity**: A gentle pull toward center point (400, 300) prevents drift

Velocities are **damped** by 0.92× each frame to prevent runaway oscillation.

### ✨ Particle System
Every 3 frames, a particle spawns from a random node, drifts outward with slight drag, and dies after 800–2000 frames. Capped at 40 particles — purely decorative ambient effect.

### 🎥 Camera
Smoothly interpolates toward a target position/zoom using exponential easing (lerp factor 0.06).

### 🔄 Main Loop
Runs at **~60 FPS** (`setInterval` at 16ms) — but notably **has no rendering code**. This is purely the simulation/data layer; presumably a separate renderer (Canvas/SVG/WebGL) reads the node/particle positions to draw them.
